quran[21]{c,v,t}:
  100,10,"and when whatever lies within the hearts is obtained—"
  100,11,"indeed, on that day, their Lord is most surely aware of them."
  101,1,"The Shocking Event!"
  101,2,"What is the Shocking Event?"
  101,3,"And what can make you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>realize what the Shocking Event is?"
  101,4,"A day when mankind become like scattered moths,"
  101,5,"and the mountains become like tufted wool."
  101,6,"So, as for the one whose scales were heavy{1}—",footnotes:1:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in pasttense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  101,7,"he is in a pleasant life."
  101,8,"But as for the one whose scales were light<a class=""sup""><sup>b </sup></a>—"
  101,9,"his home{1}is an Abyss.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is ummuhuwhich literally means ‘his mother’. According to Al-Qurtubi, Hell was described as a mother because the disbeliever heads towards it like a baby heads towards its mother.
  101,10,"And what can make you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>realize what it is?"
  101,11,"A raging fire."
  102,1,"Vying for more distracted you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>"
  102,2,"until you visited the graves."
  102,3,"But no! You<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>will come to know."
  102,4,"Once again: But no! You<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>will come to know."
  102,5,"But no! If only you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>knew with the knowledge of certitude:"
  102,6,"you will certainly <span class=""h"">see<sup foot_note=""81495"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span>purgatory."
  102,7,"Then you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>will certainly see it with the eye of certitude."
  102,8,"Then, on that day, you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>will certainly be asked about<i class=""s"">(worldly) </i>bliss."
